Out of all the words a great writer could have written - 'gynocologist' was all they could come up with. . . . :-(
FORTUNATELY ... Billie Eilish saved the DAY... when her haunting song came on right after which brought people to tears... nobody thought about that stupid joke, everyone was just busy crying. author: Maria Sardi
text:
BARBIEâ€™S FILM REVIEW
There's more than meets the eye in this well-made movie. The chosen actors were perfect for their roles. I loved the protagonist and the Kens.
As opposed to our bible story, Barbie came first, then Ken. I love that idea.
In the Barbie world, everything is perfect, pretty, and pink. But to me, it is too plastic and fake. Barbie and Ken travel to explore the real world. She becomes disappointed and saddened. She experiences emotion, a tear appears on her cheek. Ken, on the other hand, loves seeing the power and the control that men have over women and brings back these ideas into the Barbie world.
The Barbies (referring to womenâ€™s lib) fight the Kens and regain the order of their world. Barbie, however, feels different after visiting the real world. She asks permission from her creator to go back and become human.
At the end of the movie, Barbie, now Barbara, is back in the world visiting a gynecologist. She might be having a baby. She has fully accepted the human condition with all its ups and downs, and imperfections.
MORAL OF THE STORY
The movie sends several messages:
- To reconsider American values.
- There's nothing bad about aiming for perfection. We are all different and nobody is perfect but we can aspire to be the best version of ourselves.
- As for the Kens, they really need to go and find themselves.

text: National Cinema Day was awesome because I finally saw Barbie!  !!!SPOILER ALERT!!!  During part of the movie, I was wondering if "Weird Barbie" or whatever nickname Barbies gave that particular Barbie was Gymnastic Barbie.  I guess the existing Barbies were threatened in the 90s when Flat Feet Barbie aka Gymnastic Barbie was introduced to and took the world by storm.  Anyhow, the actress did an excellent job portraying high heel Barbie. Her body movements were brilliant.  I was admiring her acting very much and wondered how much she had to study the toy to practice "Barbie moves". Great job! Loved the movie.  It was colourful, funny, and definitely all about BARBIE and ken.  I suggest the lives of broken Barbies be a theme of the next Barbie movie.

author: laremabella
text: I just saw the movie. I loved my Barbie as a kid in the 90s so I was intrigued what the movie was about. The first scenes were fun but as the movie progressed, it felt quite disjointed. Parts were emotional and relatable and quite touching actually, but the conclusion was pretty cold and felt flat. Barbie leaves ken in the dust. He's left to find himself, separately,  whilst Barbie "lives her truth" as a human. This movie could have been an opportunity to heal some wounds on today's social issues and confusion, but I felt it didn't because the male was left behind. After all, viewers will have sympathised with the males (ken)  identity crisis just as much as the females (Barbie) identity crisis. That's why I felt the movies message/sentiment was kinda lost. Now that Barbie's in the real world, there's only a certain amount of time until she is missing the male energy in her life ğŸ˜‚

text: I thought this movie was going to be great because it portraits to be entertaining but instead it portraits men in a rather opinionated manner and stereotypes men in a way that is no longer real. I get that this is a feminist movie and this political movement has its ulterior motives but I was hoping that at least this film would close gender gaps and gender discrimination. The movie seems to just be a marketing plot because the final message is that in  barbie world women have the power, isn't that sexist? (it feels like they want to further perpetuate gender power differences) Why in our world dolls have to be for girls in the first place?. Mattel wants to keep making toys for girls and toys for girls where in each of the worlds one gender is in power. shouldn't both worlds be inclusive?.  . In the real world by common sense and understanding men and women can hold any job position and can have any role they wish, that is what we should pursue.  Feminism is not the way.

author: Lacy Megan
text:
I haven't seen this trailer until now, but I did see the very first trailer put out where Ken and Ken are fighting at the beach. I'm sorry, but this movie looks very cheesy and lame. My oldest daughter and I were looking forward to seeing it, because we thought it would be true to Barbie, but it looks nothing like how Barbie is usually portrayed.
In the "Barbie: Life in the Dreamhouse" animated series and the Barbie: Spy Movie, etc. Barbie is so kind and warm-hearted. In the other trailer she seems more cold and abrupt. Not to mention very weird with everyone named, "Barbie" and "Ken." Where is Teresa, Ryan, Raquel?? Â 
I think they could have picked someone to play Barbie who is already sweet in character, like Amanda Seyfried or Cameron Diaz, that already have naturally blonde hair. We get a different vibe from Margot Robbie, as she played a villain as Harley Quinn. Barbie has a tiny mouth, Margot has a beautiful, but big mouth. Â 
I think someone like Zac Efron would have been a GREAT Ken! Ken doesn't have white hair, like they gave to Ryan Gosling. It's just all wrong. I hope they do a super fun, family-friendly real life portrayal of Barbie movie; then we will see it. :) I think we'll skip this one.

author: Linda Lane
text:
One of my earliest memories is when a dog came by and stole my Barbie off the front porch in Anchorage on the porch my Grandparents built on the corner of 4th and L street (no longer there, it's Hostetler Park now). My mom said, "You shouldn't leave your things laying around." But Barbie was put away in a open top toybox.
Later I read that there was a chemical used in those first Barbies that was very appealing to dogs. So many kids lost their Barbies to dogs that they changed the formulation for the plastic.

author: The Dragonâ€™s Cup
text: First, I'm a liberal progressive... and totally support women who actually want equality and understand what that means. That said, in the not too distant future this film will most likely be looked back upon with a whole lot of embarrassment.. by pretty much everyone, probably even Gerwig, if she isn't already. It is possibly the most juvenile film ever made. Really surprised and tbh, disappointed that this film is an idol for young women. I mean.. wow, what happened!?! "Modern" (meaning today's) feminism seems predicated in delusions and seems confused and a bit lost within itself. Men have brainwashed women? That message alone is profoundly insulting to ALL women. But no... it is actually modern feminism that has brainwashed them. It has brainwashed them into literally worshipping themselves as victims of 'society' (whatever in the world that means) and victims of many other things nearly none of which reflect the past 50 years of reality. And also brainwashed into 'suddenly' believing their own sexuality was something not at all in their own control, and that their sexuality is nothing more than a false construct created by and forced upon them by patriarchy, which does not even exist. Another insult to women everywhere. These messages are utterly absurd, so much so it's actually hard to even believe they are taken seriously. It also seems like they have been brainwashed into thinking that telling other grown women how to behave and think about their own self and the world around them is good and womanly, despite being something NO man would ever even consider doing to another man OR to a woman for that matter. And now, as this movie proves, more brainwashing from what is in actuality a very small number of young, modern day versions of feminists who, tragically, cannot decipher reality from social media-driven lies and nonsense, and who happen to be concentrated in english speaking media and entertainment. They also seem to have no idea whatsoever how older "real" feminists and most men truly view the new modern feminists, which is as childish, naive, petty, insanely entitled, somewhat delusional and entirely self-absorbed people. The messages in this film are false, shockingly juvenile and ridiculous -- and yet here we are celebrating all of this in the name of ... young women.

author: Thor's Twisted Beard
text: Fair Warning: If you're considering seeing this film thinking it's a clever commentary adults can appreciate...  nooooooooo, it's not. It's a straight up kiddie film. In other words, if you wouldn't go see Spy Kids 5 you shouldn't bother going to see this. The opening was beautiful until they get to the "real world" which is just a kid's view of how adults operate things. After that it becomes a preachy bore (no matter your politics) and falls flat. But the music is great and the spectacle part of it is well done. However, the written dialog, comedic timing and editing leave a lot to be desired. Gerwig is no genius.

author: Zaiza Aria
text:
My dislike for the Barbie movie stems from several reasons:

1. The portrayal of women lacking respect for one another. And in real life women, like Barbies, are engaging in moral wrong behaviors, like stealing someone elseâ€™s partner by using attractiveness and naivety, and competing with each other regardless of the consequences.

2. Barbie often emphasizes her appearance, showing a lot of skin, and strives not to be seen as an object. Yet, it would be better to promote modesty, appropriate behavior towards men, and avoiding excessive flirting.

3. The movie seems to promote the idea of women treating men as toys to be controlled, wanting their undivided attention while not reciprocating the same feelings. This portrays an unstable and unhealthy representation of women.

4. Barbie and similar portrayals may inadvertently shape wrong attitudes in men, promoting the objectification of women and a lack of moral values.

In summary, these aspects of the Barbie movie contribute to my overall negative perception of it

And if Barbie would have been a real life person. She would have been pregnant (which is nothing wrong about that, as long she chosen the right person and is willing to commit a serious relationship in many levels) but yet she would leave the man for someone else, because she â€œdoesnâ€™t feel itâ€ The child would be collateral damage and he or she (the child) would not know what a stable and good family would look and behave like. She would then find her joy in life, multiple times and she would not care for her child in the appropriate way. Because her ego is too big and important. Her ex. Would be annoyed by her;m, so he would behave stupidly. She is constantly trying to find satisfaction in material things and in her carrier or from the love aspect. But this poor little women isnâ€™t finding it. So the world is to blame! And especially the men. If she would have raised a boy. This boy, wouldnâ€™t be raised a good men. So the vicious cycle is continuing.
And all the other women, would portray this women, as a strong feminist. Somewhere in life we have to hold on to commitment and sacrifice. Which this movie isnâ€™t showing!

author: Raindrops
text:
Why did they make such a foolish tweet? Do they think that the historical tragedy of the atomic bomb dropped on Japan is appropriate for movie promotion? That idea is extremely childish and cannot be excused as a joke. Warner Bros. should apologize for their lack of consideration and the immaturity of their movie promotion.

This historical fact took place on August 6th and 9th, 1945. The Japanese release date of this movie is August 11th, 78 years later. Recently, many Hollywood movies have included scenes that appear to respect the history of diverse ethnicities, but this promotional tweet has exposed that it's ultimately just a facade.

author: Fear the Double Bunny
text:
Creators of the movie have big issues with the logic. The movie is filled with ideas, however none of them are eveloped properly and/or resolved. The plot reminds me of people with severe ADHD issues who are switching subjects constantly forgetting what they were talking before.
What was the point of adding senior management trying to catch Barbie? She was wanting to return back to normal Barbieland (her box), why there is a need to hunt her? What was the point of getting the management to Barbieland if they just suddenly disappear here? What was the point of building the wall between Barbieland and real world if nobody wants to leave the fantasy?
Creators raise the issue of gender equality but then there is again no development here as in the end it was replaced by â€˜becoming a humanâ€™ issue all of the sudden that was also not thoroughly developed. Does reclaiming Barbies rights changes anything in real world? Are there females entering top management of the company? And why feminism wins only because men (Kens) forget to vote (again depending on men) and not because women do something meaningful?
The movie is just bunch of popular issues with no real meaning behind it included.

author: Bond Film & Collectibles
text: One of the worst films I've ever seen, and I won't apologize for thinking this. The characters are card-board cutouts that are about as bland as can be, the plot manages to feel cliche and overdone while still being so bizarre and stupid, and the dialogue/script is just awful. Like, is an "all the way to the top" button on an elevator really considered comedy? It's so bad and that's not even taking into account the awful cram-down-your-throat messaging that is, and there's no argument otherwise, meant to divide men and women. There's no subtlety or nuance at all. The real world, which is a complex place, is treated with about as much complexity as the Barbie land is. It's essentially a second fantasyland in this movie. Then, it literally just swaps Barbie land from a society ruled by women to a society ruled by men, and instead of saying how too much of either way isn't really a good thing, it instead goes for a plot about the girls retaking their country (to make is exactly as it was before, which they pretend like wasn't a problem even though it was obviously so bad that Ken was super easily and quickly manipulated by "the patriarchy") by exploiting male stereotypes. Which yes, could be funny. Stereotypes are funny. But just not in the way it's used here, it just feels really bitter. Also, a twelve-year-old girl who obviously doesn't know what fascism is making Margot Robbie cry by screaming at her that she is a fascist might be the low point in human history we've ever hit. If everyone thought the way the filmmakers of Barbie obviously do, our society would crumble. There's so many better ways to say the things a Barbie movie should say. And yes, I know, "Dur, why do you care so much it's literally a movie about dolls, dur, you spent all the time writing this comment, dur." First of all, don't pretend like this movie wasn't made literally just to be controversial. But yeah, it's because I love movies. I love good movies. And it sucks to see this flaming pile of absolute garbage get all this praise just for pretending to uplift women when you could watch an actual film that actually explores ideas and themes, and also actually empowers women. I've hated movies besides this one and have ranted about them just as much if not more than this one, so just because I took the time to write all this doesn't make Barbie special.

author: Daniel Kim
text: I just watched this movie and I thought it was da bomb!  Margot Robbie totally seemed like a doll come to life,  you could not have cast an actress who more personified Barbie, and Ryan Gosling was really, really good as Ken (although I'm biased he always plays his characters with a lot of emotion and feeling), and Kate McKinnon was honestly the surprise jewel, she was so wacky and weird and I loved her character.  Margot Robbie was both clueless about the dirty nasty real world as a plastic doll living in a perfect word but then super self aware and grows so much as a person (a doll? a human?) in the movie, and her character is suprisingly complex. I thought the aesthetics were incredible, the scenes really take your breath away, with so many vibrant colors.  The set design was pretty spectacular.  A lot of the jokes went over the head but the really basic ones ("I'm gonna beach you off") were so wacky and good.  It was funny, beautiful, and the musical and dance scenes were awesome.  I only wish there were more musical numbers.  It was wacky, silly, fast-paced, witty, sharp, funny, philosophical, existentialist, it really makes you question who you are and whether the world you are living in is real or not.

author: orangebananaxox
text:
Iâ€™m going to watch this movie tommorow with my mum and I am so excited! I am expecting a lot of people to show up because of the hype this trailer has created. Not only the actors chosen for the movie, but the soundtrack alone is incredible. Getting some of the biggest pop stars to collaborate on this album, wether in the movie or not, credits or during the actual movie, the songs are amazing. I have them all on my playlist.

Now back to the actors. Margot Robbie and Ryan Gosling were amazing choices, and I can gladly feel the same way about the other cast members. I couldnâ€™t tell you how happy I was to see Will Ferrel in the movie. I have loved watching him in the iconic elf movie, and currently re watching the us office, which he appeared on for a few episodes.

This movie is expected to be the best selling movie of 2023. I am really happy that Barbie is getting the great rating, because it deserves it. It would have cost a lot of money to create this, and the trailer alone is making me feel nostalgic. Canâ€™t wait for tommorow to see the movie!

Edit - I am also loving the little details Greta is putting in to this! She is such a creative person I love her!

author: Madelyn Abeyta
text:
After watching the trailer, I was about ready to see this movie. Then I heard about what itâ€™s really about and now you could not pay me to watch it.

Edit: Okay, what is this movie really about? Those who have seen it, please hear me out:
The reason why I havenâ€™t seen it is because Iâ€™m worried about wasting my time and money just to be cringing the whole time. Is it really about how men are creating an actual patriarchy in this world and ruling the women and therefore women need to step up and belittle the men just so they can be on top? Or is all that just satire and really poking fun at the joke feminism is today and using that to instead promote the message that women and men need each other? Because if itâ€™s the latter, count me in! And in that case, people on both sides must be taking this way too seriously. If itâ€™s the former, there is no way in heck Iâ€™m watching it. The thing is, those are completely opposite messages. They cannot both be true. So which is it?? Either this movie is as woke as some say it is or it really is as deep and moving as others say it is. But what confuses me further is some who think itâ€™s deeply moving proceed to say that the world we live in is indeed a patriarchy where itâ€™s â€œimpossibleâ€ to be a woman. That is not an empowering message! Please enlighten me!

author: Amuart
text:
Title: The Barbie Movie: Why Nikki Minaj's Involvement Raised Concerns

Introduction

The upcoming Barbie movie has generated significant excitement among fans and moviegoers, promising a fun and inspirational film that celebrates empowerment, diversity, and imagination. However, recent news about rapper Nikki Minaj's involvement in the project has sparked controversy and raised concerns among certain audiences. In this article, we will explore the reasons why some feel Nikki Minaj's inclusion may not be the best fit for the Barbie movie.

Image and Brand Alignment
Barbie has been an iconic children's toy for generations, representing ideals of beauty, elegance, and grace. Her character symbolizes a positive role model, teaching young girls about self-expression and individuality. Nikki Minaj, on the other hand, is known for her provocative and sometimes controversial image, which includes explicit lyrics, bold fashion choices, and a hyper-sexualized persona. Critics argue that the stark contrast between Nikki Minaj's brand and Barbie's wholesome image may send conflicting messages to young viewers.

Parental Concerns
Given that the Barbie movie is primarily aimed at young audiences, parents play a crucial role in determining its appropriateness for their children. Some parents may feel uneasy about Nikki Minaj's presence in the movie due to her adult-oriented content and provocative public image. These concerns may lead parents to question the film's suitability for their impressionable children, potentially impacting the movie's overall success at the box office.

Misalignment with the Movie's Message
The Barbie movie is expected to deliver empowering messages about self-acceptance, resilience, and the importance of kindness. While Nikki Minaj is undoubtedly a successful and talented artist, her brand and lyrics have often been criticized for promoting materialism, vanity, and confrontational attitudes. Critics argue that her involvement in the film could divert the focus away from the movie's positive themes and risk sending mixed messages to young viewers.

Missed Opportunities for Diverse Representation
Diversity and inclusivity have become essential aspects of modern storytelling, with a growing demand for representation of various cultures and backgrounds in movies. Some critics argue that Nikki Minaj's casting may not be the most inclusive choice, as it perpetuates the stereotype of the sassy and outspoken Black woman. While it is crucial to celebrate diverse voices in film, some argue that the character should have been portrayed by an actress who aligns more closely with Barbie's uplifting and empowering image.

Conclusion

The Barbie movie has the potential to become a heartwarming and impactful film for audiences worldwide. However, Nikki Minaj's involvement has sparked debate and concerns about the film's messaging and suitability for young viewers. While Nikki Minaj is undoubtedly a talented and successful artist, some argue that her image and brand may not align seamlessly with Barbie's empowering and inspiring character.

In the pursuit of promoting diversity and inclusivity, it is vital for filmmakers to make thoughtful choices that do not undermine the core message of a beloved and iconic character like Barbie. As the film progresses, it remains to be seen how Nikki Minaj's role will be portrayed and how the film's overall impact will be received by audiences of all ages.

I neither love nor hate Barbie but M. Robbie's performance in Wolf of Wall Street was superb.

author: Angela Burnett
text: From this trailer it's looking like Barbie is being portrayed as a superficial, party girl and Ken as sexist. I don't like that comparison or the comparison that Barbie is so detached from the real world. Other than the "perfect" figure Barbie has everything else about her is left up to your imagination as a child. And for girls Barbie could do anything that was literally her slogan we girls can do anything right  Barbie. So why are we taking that away from girls and dumbing Barbie down to a superficial party girl who's all about her wardrobe and possessions? And Ken being her best friend or boyfriend knows Barbie can be anything such as a doctor, astronauts, veterinarian, etc... so why is he acting like there can't be a female doctor in this movie? I don't understand the whole Barbie needs to get in touch with the real world theme, is it not real that a woman can do anything? Can we not be doctors, lawyers, president, etc...  I'm going to watch the movie before making my mind up about it but if it truly is how the trailer makes it appear I know I'm not going to be a fan, because my Barbie was always a strong independent woman and her having a great wardrobe and knowing how to have fun didn't take away from that. Her house and vehicle was thanks to her success of working hard.

author: Mike21
text:
Just watched this in theaters last night. Here is my take on it without any spoilersâ€¦.

PROS: lots of actors and actresses who are household names and a handful of laugh out loud moments. The first 15-20 minutes were probably the best part of the film.

CONS: the movie was clearly political and had an agenda of feminism and toxic masculinity. In barbieland all the Kenâ€™s are pathetic idiots and have no purpose in life. In the real world men are toxic and ruin everything. The storyline was pretty vanilla and there was a point it felt like the movie dragged on. The film heavily relied on random actors popping in and out who were household names instead of actually keeping you entertained because the story was captivating. The plot was so basic youâ€™d think the target audience were children, but half the jokes were targeted to adults to the point the 7 year old girl sitting behind me kept asking her mom â€œwhat does that mean mommy?â€

Iâ€™m sure a lot of people will find it entertaining, but I just wasnâ€™t a fan of the divisive nature of the film.

Overall, I would recommend though, whether you hate or love Barbie.

author: Philip Robins
text:
Q anyone watch the Barbie movie? Bc all the reviews I am watching are singing praise about how progressive it is, and I'm just like, it feels like it makes a joke out of feminism and minimizes corporate greed
A It does all of those things. It ultimately is still a product but the movie does go in a direction you wouldn't necessarily expect. Yes, it minimizes the corporate greed of Mattel, but they don't completely shy away from that either. For a Hollywood blockbuster it is very progressive
It has a very coherent feminist message in a way that few summer tentpole movies have ever had.

author: Anna C
text:
The movie had no depth, in my opinion. Its dialogue was pretty flat and even the intro line / hook up line was average (you could tell the movie was going to be average; Hollywood really needs to find good scriptwriters again, no joke). It didn't tell anything new and in my opinion, it had no conclusion at all. Or even a solid general idea, it was just all over the place. I also wished it would have stuck to just one genre / feeling : make it full comedy, or make it more emotional or something. But it was all over the place. I thought it would at least be witty, but it was not. I would rate it 6/10 and if I had the chance, I would not watch it again in a cinema. It is not cinema-level worthy (but it turns out 90% of Hollywood's movies are not cinema-worthy these days). Even the cinematography / picture was really average. It was commercial from beginning to end and the most entertaining parts were Ken' parts... in a movie about Barbie, it turns out Ken was the most entertaining one. That says a lot. The only other most notable scene was America Ferrera's speech, but even that one was just spitting out a list of already known-facts and in the most average way (again, nothing witty, original or artistic about the speech itself). Kids will probably like it... but even back in the days, movies for kids had subtle lines that only adults would understand, and yet there were so tastefully implemented in the movies. If I were to be a kid again and someone would make me choose between this Barbie movie and let's say... Toy Story, then Toy Story would win by a mile distance and in a heartbeat.
I don't know... I just wished all this promotion was for something.

author: Jodi Leonforte
text: Too bad the actual film was not this upbeat. They should've charged us $23 for this trailer, these are all the scenes we wanted anyway. I wasn't expecting the soapbox preaching on rights and standards because nowhere does it feature in this preview. Because I'm sure people wouldn't have gone to see this film if they had emphasized that material. I don't know many people who seek to pay money to be told how life is full of struggle and double-standards. I can live that misery for free, thanks. I left the theater feeling down on myself and society in general. The whole tone was sour, sarcastic, and a real bummer overall. And as trailers are good at doing, the brief allusion to the Barbie Girl song dominates this trailer like it's a prominent feature in the actual film. In reality, it's at the very end credits and more like this soft background melody to the overlaid song (which I wasn't a fan of). And if you think I got the wrong take on this movie, go to the part where the white-presenting father is ACTIVELY trying to learn his wife and biracial daughter's language, and how they shoot him down and mock his efforts. So much for fairness and consideration of others! The tone of this movie was rules are for thee and not for me, or I guess "rules are for men because women have been put down for so long that it's fine if we're impatient or nasty because, well, we struggled for so long so it's our time to have power, and politeness is fluff anyway". You watch this trailer thinking the energy is one way, and then you walk out of the theater realizing it was a complete veneer over heaps of negativity. There was no inspiration, no hope that it'll get better, just constant reminders of how awful and tough it is to be a woman...what?? Why did I pay actual money to hear all that? I really wish I'd never seen this film.

author: The Postal Dude
text:
Iâ€™ve never seen the movie, but I did read the story and turns out the movie is really bad. I was very disappointed because the trailers were awesome. The marketing and the cast are good, unfortunately the story and characters are awful. It is the most disappointing movie of the year. Go see Oppenheimer and Sound Of Freedom instead everyone.

Spoilers:

The movie begins with Barbie land, a matriarchal society where women are self confident, self sufficient and successful while the Ken (Men) counterparts spend the days doing recreational activities at the beach. The Barbies hold all the job positions such as doctors, lawyers and politicians. That is the opening premise. Later on, Barbie and Ken went to the real world and they found out that itâ€™s a very misogynistic place. Ken brings the patriarchy to Barbie land and the Kens took over and became rulers in Barbie world. The Barbies want to turn Barbie world back into a matriarchal society and they used the power of feminism to stop the Kens and turn their world back to what it was before.

That is the whole story for the movie. The movieâ€™s message â€œsexism is badâ€ couldâ€™ve been handled very well, unfortunately it was handled very poorly.

Hereâ€™s how to fix it: Barbie and Ken went to the real world and found out itâ€™s a very misogynistic place. Barbie and Ken realized that Barbie world has the same problem (Itâ€™s a very misandric place (In other words the two worlds both have sexism in them)) and they both agreed to work together to stop misogyny and misandry in both worlds.

There. I fixed it. That is what the movieâ€™s story shouldâ€™ve been, unfortunately thatâ€™s not what we got. Instead, itâ€™s yet another â€œmen bad women goodâ€ movie by woke Hollywood where the men are portrayed as dumb, weak and evil while the women are portrayed as smart, strong and good in comparison (Remember Last Jedi, SheHulk and Ghostbusters 2016?). In conclusion, this movie is a disappointing dumpster fire and I hope it fails. Critical Drinker is right about this dumpster fire.

author: Lianna Pfister
text:
I left the theater pleased with this movie and the more I think about it the more upset I am.
The first half hour or so was the best part. I loved watching Barbieland. Helen Mirrenâ€™s narration is also 10/10. Itâ€™s a funny movie.
I thought the film did a good job reminding us that we are supposed to be suspending our disbelief; the â€œreal worldâ€ isnâ€™t actually the real world. No one was ever told anything like â€˜ALL women experience misogyny in the Real World,â€™ which I really appreciate.
A really big issue is that every single female in this movie is good and every male is bad. Maybe Alan is a good guy, but heâ€™s barely a character. ALL of the men we see are incompetent and ALL of the women are wonderful. Even when the Barbies realize that the Kens need to feel they have a right to exist, the Kens are still portrayed as idiots. It couldâ€™ve been a really interesting examination of inequality, but I guess the creators thought misandry would be better.

author: Adonijah Mehr
text: Im a huge movie fan. I will watch just about any movie that comes out in the theater. I do do any research in advance as I do not want to go into the movie biased and influenced by other peoples opinions. But I just watched this movie today. It literally was one of the worst movies Ive ever seen. Like most people I go to the theater to have fun, have a different experience then watching at home and to be entertained. This movie was nothing more then a 4th wave feminist filled, men hating propaganda spewing piece of trash. And the worst part is it does nothing but put a divide between men and women. At first Ken loves Barbie and she doesnt like him and acts like she doesnt need him or want him. Then Ken turns into an extreme idiot and they writers makes him hate her, which in turn makes her hate him even more. And the worst part is there is no happy ending where they end up together. She still rejects him in the end. If this world would stop putting men and women against each other and start focusing on the differences that we have that makes us compatible for each other then this world would be a better place, more peaceful, happier place. Instead the movie does nothing but destroy men, promote extreme feminism and send a ton of wrong messages and mindsets to young people in our society. I could say plenty more about how bad this movies was but I will simply say this. Its one of the worst movies ive ever seen and I would definitely not recommend it to anyone and most definitely not for any children or young people to see.

author: Vincenzo
text:
I watched the movie. I can say that the cast, the script, the special effects are really well done and have been studied in detail. the plot, on the other hand, didn't make me very happy. The film is based precisely on some social situations, and criticized how the real world sees women and men comparing it to Barbieland. The social critique was spot on at first but as the film progresses this critique begins to convey no correct meaning. What was supposed to be a funny and dystopian film turned out to be a work made following the rules of "politically correct" but transmitting them in the wrong way. The ending of the movie leaves you not satisfied but very disagreeing with what you just watched.
vote 6/10

text: So many things when I think about Barbie. I was born in 1993 and growing up I remember the issues that people had with Barbie dolls because it was always coming out on the news. It was either too sexual and it was playing with childrens minds by thinking am i going to look just like Barbie when I grow up. It was also a way of giving the children an open mind on who they were going to be and then the ads and commercials were on point when it came to that. Then the bratz came in and it was the same issues because it was more sexual due to the fashion and clothes that they wore but they were also looked upon as unacceptable due to the fact that they made bratz dolls based on different skin tones and hair and the skin tone represented a different race because a Hispanic can pass by as maybe a French due to the skin tone. 1969 was when ken came in. The first Barbie doll was actually a blond and brunette but it looked more like a reddish hair color. In the 80s was when they finally had a Latina barbie doll, but either way Barbie is always looked as a blonde and light skin. If they wanted they could use a different color Barbie in the movie or whatever in general. I mean they do have a Barbie who isnâ€™t blonde talking about racism with ken sitting next to her in the Barbie cartoons

author: Friso Flor 3
text: I was be able to attend the pre premiere of this movie and I have to say this movie was unexpectetly good and this comes from a non Barbie fan. Barbie is the role Robbie was clearly born to play. Ryan Gosling and Simu Liu were incredible too and actually the whole cast of this movie shines ! Barbie is a brilliantly executed, incredibly fun, brightly colored, completely logical feminist statement that should be remembered come awards season. Ultimately, Barbie is so many things: a stereotype, a toy, an idea; a vessel of imagination; a cultural relic. But in Gerwig's trusted hands, this is Barbie like you've never seen her before.

author: Benjamin Kristall
text: Seems like transforming a plastic doll into a live action movie actor isn't implausible. However, this story being the true life of Barbie (actor or the doll) isn't a reasonable assumption. Any confusion caused by this movie's portrayal of the events of Barbie not being distinguished from actual reality is easy to avoid. Hence, there isn't any reason to think of this film as having meaningful relevance to real people's lives. I wonder if the most important theme (subtext) of this movie is to encourage the idea of playing with Barbie is for those people that have trouble facing up to reality? ...Let's go party.

text: Plastic, fake , bad blinkin example for girls! Ok, so there's a barbie in a wheelchair, and a barbie with Down Syndrome, and also thin barbie and curvy, but so... it's still focused on the crappy fake, glitter, rainbows and butterflies theme.  I am not projecting- I just want to know: is there any meaning about inner beauty, strength and  a  message to reflect on in this ?  Maybe they just made the dolls I mentioned above to get people like me to shut up. I love glitter and pink too, but glitter fades  had  will dry up or be washed  away  high heels break, nail polish chips, make up smudges. Self belief, dignity, self respect and inner strength are FOREVER.  Ok, I'm waiting for people to have a go at me.... I am not judging people who like barbies or this movie, but everyone on you tube is entitled to free speech !

author: LKNANML
text:
My GI Joes battled my sisters Barbies until the great Cabbage Patch Kid attack of 1982. It was a massacre! Barbie and GI Joe put their differences aside and gathered all the allies they could. My Little Pony, Strawberry Shortcake, Rainbow Brite, Rose Petal Place, MASK, Star Wars, Transformers, Care Bears, Masters of the Universe, MUSCLE, Sky Commanders, Tron, those horses I can't remember the name of...
IT WAS AN EPIC BATTLE that raged for years. In 1983 the top secret weapon failed to end the war. Code name Atari 2600. It was taken out by a single Alien.
It wasn't until 1985 till a new weapon to end the war was made. The PC.. Followed by the NIN.....
The war....... well actually the war never ended or at least I wasn't there for it.
I started playing PC and Nintendo games and pretty much dropped all other toys.. I think GI Joe married Barbie or something like that. They moved in together in my sisters room with some of the others. Then I found girls and that was really the end for me as commander in charge of stopping the Cabbage Patch Kid takeover....

This movie looks funny and original.

author: Nate Alter
text: Barbie will embarrass and humiliate Oppenheimer at the box office. Anyone born 1965 and up knows and remembers the cultural impact of Barbie. When we see that distinctive pink color on anything, the first thing that pops into our minds is Barbie. That pink color is subconsciously deeply connected to Barbie. We see a pink Cadillac, we think Barbie. We see a pink shirt, we think Barbie. We see a pink crayon, we think Barbie. We see a pink trash can, we think Barbie. We see a bottle of Pepto-Bismol, we think Barbie. The question is NOT which film is the best film. The question is which film will people rather pay to see. It's summertime and the kids are off school, that's the answer. And it is the first ever official live action Barbie anything, so of course people are going to see Barbie.

text: Extrapolated on a more profound level, I see this story as the story of Buddha.  Both lived in a perfect world and had everything. They venture out into the real world and learn about real life.  Coincidentally, both names begin with B.  But Barbie is really so American in such a commercial and capitalistic way.  And in a way, Barbie is kind of like the American philosophy towards life.

author: The Communication Coach
text: Hollyweird!! The movie looks like it could be da bomb, or a bomb. Only time will tell, but Will Ferrell is one of the worst wannabe 'actors' ever, he's been the highest-paid flop for years now, though no one knows why. It's too bad that so few good and original movies are produced anymore that we have to watch comic books and toys online instead. I wish they'd gone with new actors to play Ken and Barbie, as all I see so far is Harley Quinn and the guy who dated a mannequin, but, of course, I never played with either one; my friends and I were too busy blowing up army men and GI Joes with firecrackers like they were in real battle. I don't HATE it, but I need to kind of get used to it. It does look unique at the very least and I love the glitzy campiness of it all. I wasn't too sure of the casting at first, but Margot Robbie's Barbie has grown on me (Kelly Sheridan will always be my favorite Barbie, but I'm bias because she's Canadian.) But Ryan Gosling as Ken was an excellent casting choice! Might give this one a watch, bring my fashion dolls with me!

author: semoremo
text: I really don't understand how someone might think Ryan Gosling isn't THE perfect casting choice for Ken. Not only does he do a TERRIFIC job capturing the himbo essence of Ken, but he also matches perfectly with Margot's vibe. And to anyone saying he looks "too old" to play Ken... every single actor playing someone in the Barbie World looks to be around the same age as he does. You can clearly tell these aren't teens or 20 year olds, so if they had gotten someone younger to play Ken, he would've been the one looking out of place. And either way, isn't everyone preaching about "casting the most talented actor" instead of someone else for a specific reason (in this case, age)? I don't know who else must've auditioned for Ken, and you can dislike the theme of the movies Ryan Gosling has acted in, but you can't tell me that isn't an amazing actor.

Ive never really been too into this movie considering ive outgrown my barbie phase, but watching the old lady interact with barbie and the group of girls saying that they havent played barbie since they were five struck a cord in my heart.

Ive grown up loving the dolls, ive got a whole box of dolls in a storage box when i was younger, waking up to play with them every morning when i was younger, binging barbie movies non stop.

And although im not into barbie anymore, theres still something sentimental about it that just makes me feel a little more interested in the movie, maybe its my inner little girl from all those years ago who loved barbie so much. Maybe i would go and check this movie out, for her

author: ShimmySnail
text:
I say that Barbie was actually "progressive" because 50 or so years ago, she was dismissed by some feminists of the day since she had unrealistic physical measurements. But she wasn't a housewife (or a wife), she wasn't a secretary, she wasn't a waitress, and she doesn't have kids. She's a doctor, an astronaut, a marine biologist, an airline pilot. Granted, one in high heels with a wasp waist. But remember, anorexia nervosa and bulimia were not household words back then, let alone fears spread to every tween on their handheld ADHD device of choice.

Another YouTuber, Beau of the Fifth Column, countered some critics who thought the new Snake Eyes (from G.I. Joe) was too woke because he was portrayed by an Asian actor (with the very Asian name of Henry Golding). Honestly I always assumed he was Asian because he looks like a ninja from a 1980s action movie. But in any case, Beau mentioned that even in the comic books from the 1980s, G.I. Joe introduced military characters who were: women, veterans suffering from PTSD, liberal politicians who don't behave in a tropey manner, even a pacifist. So, they were always "woke." Or progressive, whatever you want to call it, even back when they were dismissed as a craven recruitment toy.

I'm sure that people will say that Mattel has been dragged into the culture wars and there will be calls for a boycott of Barbie who used to be such a perfect Reagan Woman, but it's simply not true. Barbie is at once feminine, and a role model for girls who want to have all the choices in life that straight white men have.

author: ShimmySnail
text: The whole "if you hate Barbie, this movie is for you" is so true.  I never liked Barbie, because I'm a boy, and dolls are dumb.  But when Barbie: Life in the Dreamhouse came out, and my daughter started watching it, it was HILARIOUS, and I just fell in love with it.  Hilarious, great writing, and I realized that Barbie had been progressive for a long time.  She was a doctor, astronaut, marine biologist, all that.  And I told my co-workers that exact thing, "If you love Barbie, you'll love Barbie: Life in the Dream house.  If you hate Barbie, you'll love Barbie: Life in the Dreamhouse.  It makes fun of itself, it's progressive, great voice talents, it's very adult."  And nobody knew what I was talking about, even the women in the room.  I am looking forward to taking the whole family to this!

author: Nastja Fisunova
text:
I'm afraid, the main idea will be "the new barbie line - where Barbie has plain legs, her clothes have no glamour, her "dreamhouse" has stairs etc. - is better, than old. That's why the main topic of the movie will be about changes. She doesn't want to wear ugly boots with no high heels, but in the end she will use them with the smile on her face."
But no, the present line is ugly. The clothes, shoes and accessories don't match eatch other neither in colors, nor in style. The quality of dolls, clothes and accessories become worse and worse year after year - cheap textures, clothes are made poorly, plastic instead of material clothing, her legs and arms are not flexible anymore (the old barbie fashionista dolls had plastic limbs, currently it's avaliable only for expensive dolls), hair is not so long, thick and soft. Overall, the Barbie doll is not a fashion icon any more. She is just an ordinary doll with zero taste.

So she poured her poor, misguided heart into a Barbie Movie. As for anyone who HATES Barbie, I can't imagine putting this much energy into a mean spirited mockery.  Oh put them in the real world. Lets look back at the He-Man movie. The movie that killed Cannon Films. No. Just no. LOL Margot, Ryan, be better, do better. This is some 1st Mario Movie, Speed Racer nonsense.

author: Jamie Grant Adaire
text: Everything Greta Gerwig seems to do has a euphoric, nostalgic, ephemeral vibe to it. And although each stylistically different, that puts her in contention with other great stylized directors such as Sofia Coppola and Wes Anderson. Now with Barbie we can expect a sincerity and humanity, like any of Gerwigs previous films, but this film will have an extra sparkle. So with the stylistic choices made for the sake of the theme of Barbie, one should wonder if this film in any way will be an indicator of Gerwigs stylization. After all, there is an alleged rule in the industry that states a directors style is usually beginning to show and then stick by the directors third movie. This will be Greta Gerwigs fourth film as a director. So what should we expect to see her bring from films like â€œLittle Womenâ€ and â€œLady Birdâ€? Very excited for this!

Children and Parents Learn the Truth Together
A toddler walked into the gallery and refused to leave. His parents followed him into the gallery and looked at every poster closely and listened to the introductions the entire way around. The father said it was his first time to learn this, and he was shocked to hear about live organ harvesting. He said he would let more people know about these crimes.

A student received a flier about the exhibition on her way to private school. She wanted to see it immediately. Her mother persuaded her to complete her studies first and visit the gallery after school. She and her mother came to the gallery together.

The girl was shocked by the CCPâ€™s atrocities and took a copy of each flyer to study later and to share the information with her classmates. Her mother said that it was the first time she had heard such unacceptable things. She hoped that such atrocities could be stopped as soon as possible, and she encouraged the organizers to continue their endeavors.

author: Chne wart
text:
Investigative Journalist: Timeline of Organ Harvesting in China

Independent journalist Ethan Gutmann

Investigative journalist Ethan Gutmann talked about the history and current state of organ harvesting in China. In the late 1980s, extraction of organs from executed prisoners became routine. After the CCP began to suppress Falun Gong in 1999, the persecution became the largest campaign in China since the Cultural Revolution.

â€œIn 2001, with approximately two million Falun Gong [practitioners] in the Chinese [labor camp] system, Falun Gong prisoners are singled out for retail organs only examinations... kidneys, liver, heart, and to some extent the lungs, ...â€ explained Gutmann in his presentation. â€œBy 2002, the wait time for foreign organ tourists are reported to be two weeks or less.â€

By 2003, detained Tibetans and Christians were also examined for their organs. In 2014, police officers in China went to Falun Gong practitionersâ€™ homes to take blood and DNA samples compatible with tissue typing. After 2016, the CCP also ordered blood sampling from Uyghurs for DNA and tissue matching. That is, the CCP has expanded organ harvesting from executed prisoners to detained Falun Gong practitioners, to Tibetans, Christians, and Uyghurs.

Earlier this year, the International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation announced a policy of refusing research articles from mainland China due to the transplant abuse. Gutmann referred to it as a courageous move. Furthermore, he proposed that research articles from Chinese doctors or nurses involving organ harvesting not appear in Western medical journals. In addition, they should be banned from medical conferences and scientific collaborations. Related medical device sales should also be stopped, he added.

text:
A poster exhibition against the CCPâ€™s live organ harvesting organized by the Transplant Tourism Research Association (TTRA) was held in the gallery of North Plaza, Saitama City, from April 29 to May 2, 2023. A total of 40 posters exposing the Chinese Communist Partyâ€™s (CCP) crimes of organ harvesting from living Falun Gong practitioners were exhibited.

This poster exhibition showcased the winning works of the 2020 International Anti-Organ Harvesting Poster Contest jointly organized by three NGOs from Japan, South Korea and Taiwan. Visitors to the exhibition learned about the evil nature of the CCP and gained a deeper understanding of what Falun Gong (also called Falun Dafa) is about. Many people said that they are willing to do their part to stop the CCPâ€™s atrocities.


A poster exhibition against live organ harvesting was held in the gallery of North Plaza, Saitama City, Saitama Prefecture from April 29 to May 2, 2023.





Art Designer Attends the Exhibition for Three Consecutive Days
An art designer in her twenties came to the exhibition every day for three consecutive days after work. She said that the posters were well designed and vividly presented the evil of the CCP. She said the exhibition is a very good information portal to learn the facts. â€œI would like to support this movement in order to save the children and people,â€ she said.

She searched for information about Falun Gong and the persecution online after visiting the exhibition for a second time, but couldnâ€™t understand why the CCP wanted to persecute a group of people cultivating Truthfulness-Compassion-Forbearance. She asked a guide this question on the third day. A Falun Gong practitioner volunteering at the exhibition told her about her family members who are being persecuted in China. The art designer was very touched and thanked the organizers.

author: SwiftFox Productions
text:
I'm tentatively excited for this movie but, Ken not being able to recognize the concept of a female doctor does concern me a bit. I mean, literally, the first Doctor Barbie came out in the 1970s and there have been dozens of variations made since. There have been way way way more Barbies released as some kind of doctor than Kens ever have been (literally only 5 Ken dolls have been doctors, ever)! There are over a dozen Barbies that are just general doctors/surgeons, not even counting the ones that are specifically pediatricians or dentists or vets or eye doctors or paramedics etc, etc, etc... So, yeah, Ken should be well aware of the concept of a female doctor by now. ğŸ™„
(In other words, that was a pretty weak joke to choose for the movie's trailer...)

author: Josh R
text:
Such a weird concept. This is such a 90s idea- bringing a fantasy character to the real world. Those never worked in wonderful ways before- time will tell if this will be any better.
I can already tell what this movie is going to do- juxtapose the silliness of Barbie's world to the harsh realities of the real world and how Barbie promotes a form of misogynist ideals from its era and how that is problematic and we have a chance now to be better.
I'm just worried about the writing. I find Noah Baumbach can sometimes be really flat and take a long time to get to the point. But we'll see.
I do wonder how this movie is going to do given how much I am certain its going to lean into feminist idology. I think feminism is good at its core, but if all it has to say is "men bad, women oppressed" then this movie has nothing going for it in the end. Every time that is done is a missed opportunity to say anything of actual substance and no one will hear you. The whole point of feminism is that everyone is equal. There is a good story in there.

i think it would be perfect for you to check out BLACKSWAN's new comeback KARMA music video!! :))

They are a kpop group only composed with foreigners (so non asian members) apart from one that is Indian, and actually the 1st Indian kpop idol ever : Sriya Lenka

Also, they shoot the MV in INDIA, which is a great representation of the country because they learned about the culture with Sriya's family in her hometown!!

There are really talented and deserve some recognition!! So please check it ou!! Thank you all!! :))

text:
Watched that girl step out of her damn heels on her toes like a normal Barbie, and my literal autistic brain was like, â€œI KNEW BARBIE WAS AUTISTIC THIS WHOLE TIME WITH ALL THESE STIMS AND SPECIAL INTERESTS!!! THE TOE-WALKING CONFIRMS IT!â€ ğŸ¤£ğŸ¤£ğŸ¤£ I donâ€™t know why the thought crossed my mind only just now for the first time in my life (as clearly Barbies are generally on their toes because of heels), but the thought of Barbie being neurodivergent despite me joking to myself seems accurate in a sense. I think watching a real human be on their toes after they step out of their shoes triggered the thought and made it feel realistic.

I swear, now my ever-changing special interests will now include me doing research over Barbie and neurodivergence.

Proving highly adaptable, it entered service with the Navy in 1961 before it was adopted by the United States Marine Corps and the United States Air Force, and by the mid-1960s it had become a major part of their air arms. Phantom production ran from 1958 to 1981 with a total of 5,195 aircraft built, making it the most produced American supersonic military aircraft in history, and cementing its position as a signature combat aircraft of the Cold War.

text:
I am not crazy! I know she swapped those opinions! I knew it was a franchise movie. Based on a pre-existing property. As if I could ever make such a mistake. Never. Never! I just - I just couldn't resist it. She - she casted Gosling, he's literally me. You think this is something? You think this is bad? This? This chicanery? She's done worse. Little Women! Are you telling me that a film just happens to make Alcott exciting? No! She orchestrated it! Greta! She made me interested in pre-existing properties! And I watched it! And I shouldn't have. I added it to my own Letterboxd! What was I thinking? She'll never change. She'll never change! Ever since she started directing, always the same! Even made mumblecore interesting! But not our Greta! Couldn't be precious Greta! Stealing them blind! And Barbie made me believe in the power of cinema!? What a sick joke! I should've stopped her when I had the chance! And you - you have to stop her!

(Just kidding. Long live Barbie! Greta forever!)

text: Using the Brady Bunch Movie formula and it's perfect for this project.  A "capsule" broken open exposing the protected main characters to reality, where the conflict will be who's will is stronger.  "Reality" or the spirit of the character.  Spoiler Alert, it's the spirit of the character.  Some of the characters old and unnecessary traits will have to be shed, but the spirit of the character remains unchanged and even more committed to their own light.  Follow me for more storytelling and filmmaking insights.
